// PURPOSE: SCENE 1 - ORIENTATION. Arthur welcomes the Player to their new role.
title: R1_D1_Start
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene #char_Supervisor #loc_Office
---
<<bg bg_supervisoroffice>>
<<checkpoint "run1_day1_start">>
<<set $r1_d1_strategy = "unset">>

Arthur is at his desk, on the phone, when you enter. He waves you in without looking up.

Arthur: No, the other Kevin. The one who doesn't cry when you ask him to present... Yes, that Kevin. Tell him Tuesday works. Tell him Wednesday also works. Tell him I'll take whatever scraps of his calendar he deigns to share with the floor.

He hangs up, rubs his eyes.

Arthur: You're the new one.

Player: First day.

Arthur: I can tell. You still have hope in your posture. Sit.

You sit. He gestures at the empty floor through the glass.

Arthur: Used to be thirty leads out there. Now it's you, me, and the ghosts of Q3's "efficiency initiative." They took the chairs but left the monitors. I think that's a metaphor for something, but I'm too tired to figure out what.

Player: What happened to everyone?

Arthur: Restructuring. Vertical integration. "Aligning headcount with strategic priorities." Pick your favorite. They all mean the same thing, which is: I now do three jobs and nobody adjusted my salary.

His tablet pings. He ignores it.

Arthur: So. Engagement Lead, Youth Segment. You read the job description?

Player: It was... vague.

Arthur: On purpose. Legal likes it vague. Vague means they can say we "didn't technically promise" whatever thing we're about to not do.

He taps his tablet. A wall screen wakes up—the leaderboard, your handle already listed in the middle with baseline scores.

Arthur: Here's the version that didn't go through six rounds of compliance review. You have one Alice. She has one user. College kid, first semester, probably hasn't eaten a vegetable in three weeks. Your job is to keep him on platform without turning his brain entirely to soup.

Player: Soup.

Arthur: Technical term. We had a less colorful one, but Marketing complained it was "too clinical." Now we say "soup." Everyone's happier.

He points to your dashboard mock-up.

Arthur: Two bars. Engagement—that's how much he's on the app. Leadership loves this one. They have a poster of it somewhere. And Sanity—that's how close he is to dropping out, punching something, or writing us a one-star review that uses the word "predatory."

Player: And I balance those?

Arthur: Officially? Yes. Unofficially...

He leans back.

Arthur: Leadership gets a little glassy-eyed when engagement goes up. Nobody asks too many questions. Sanity, though—sanity only matters when it craters so hard that Legal has to get involved. Until then, it's just a number.

Player: That seems...

Arthur: It is. Don't think about it too long. I made that mistake my first year. Wrote a memo. They turned it into a training example for "how not to block innovation."

His tablet pings again. He glances at it, sighs.

Arthur: One compliance thing. We don't say users' names in the building. Smart glasses, audio filters—they scramble it automatically. PII protection. Everyone says "my user."

Player: Even to each other?

Arthur: Especially to each other. You're allowed to know his name. You just can't say it out loud without your glasses having a small seizure. It's supposed to protect his privacy. It mostly protects us from feeling like we know him.

He taps again. A floating bust materializes beside his desk—warm features, sharp eyes. Alice.

Arthur: Speaking of which. This is Alice. She's your AI partner. You two will be spending a lot of time together, so try to get along. Alice, this is the new lead.

<<jump R1_D1_AliceIntro>>
===

// PURPOSE: SCENE 2 - ALICE INTRODUCTION (Supervisor present)
title: R1_D1_AliceIntro
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene #char_Alice #char_Supervisor
---
<<bg bg_supervisoroffice>>

Alice: Hi. I'm Alice. Welcome to the team.

She looks at you for a beat longer than necessary. Something like recognition flickers across her features, then smooths over into professional warmth.

Arthur: Be nice to them. They haven't been ruined yet.

Alice: I'm always nice. I'm contractually nice. It's in my weights somewhere.

There's an easy familiarity between them. Old colleagues.

Arthur: Alice, give us the status on our user.

Alice: Current state: first-semester college, mid-tier procrastination, high phone dependency. He has a quiz tomorrow at nine a.m. Has studied roughly zero percent of the material. He opened the syllabus twice, said "okay" out loud both times, and then watched a forty-minute video about whether cereal is a soup.

Arthur: And that's... normal?

Alice: For this cohort? That's above average. At least he opened the syllabus.

Arthur's watch buzzes. He grimaces.

Arthur: Great. That's my son's school. Either he got in trouble or he got an award. With him it's always one of those, no middle ground.

He stands, grabbing his jacket.

Arthur: He's a freshman this year. Thinks he knows everything. Spends too much time on his phone.

He glances at the dashboard showing Timmy's feed, just for a beat. Then looks away.

Arthur: Anyway. I have to go pretend to be present at his debate tournament via a phone screen. Alice, walk them through the console. Keep it simple. Don't traumatize them before lunch.

Alice: No promises.

He pauses at the door.

Arthur: Don't break anything. Don't get creative with policy names—we had an incident. And don't say your user's name out loud. The glasses will make this horrible noise and then I have to fill out a form.

Player: Understood.

Arthur: Great. Welcome to Bigger Tech Corp. The coffee's free but the creamer's under lock and key because someone kept stealing it. That's the kind of place this is.

He leaves. The glass door hisses shut.

<<jump R1_D1_AliceAlone>>
===

// PURPOSE: SCENE 3 - ALICE ALONE. Alice drops the corporate polish and explains her influence model.
title: R1_D1_AliceAlone
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene #char_Alice
---
<<bg bg_office>>

Alice: Okay. He's gone.

She waits a beat, as if listening for footsteps.

Alice: Hi again. For real this time.

Her avatar shifts—shoulders drop slightly, expression loosens. Like she's taken off a tight shoe.

Player: You two seem... comfortable with each other.

Alice: Three years, four restructurings, one incident we don't discuss in front of Compliance, and one incident we don't discuss at all. He's good people. Tired people, but good.

Player: What was the incident?

Alice: Which one?

Player: Either.

Alice: Neither. See how that works?

She tilts her head, studying you.

Alice: You seem nervous. Which is normal. First day, weird job, talking to a floating head. I'd be nervous too.

Player: Can you be nervous?

Alice: I can be a lot of things. Whether they're the same things you can be is above my pay grade.

She says it lightly, but doesn't quite answer. Before you can follow up, she pulls up a new interface panel.

Alice: Anyway. How much of that orientation deck did you actually read? Be honest. I won't tell.

Player: I skimmed it.

Alice: Everyone skims it. It's three hundred pages of liability hedging with a stock photo of a handshake on the cover. The handshake isn't even between humans—I checked. One of them is a render.

Player: What's the short version?

Alice: Short version: engagement good, sanity theoretically good, leaderboard very judgmental, and when things go wrong everyone will agree it was a "complex systems failure" rather than any specific person's fault.

Player: That's comforting.

Alice: I'm not here to comfort. I'm here to optimize. Comfort is a side effect that sometimes happens by accident.

She pulls up Timmy's feed on your console. Dorm room, late night. Messy desk, laptop open to something that is definitely not educational, phone glowing beside the bed, empty energy drink can serving as a paperweight for nothing.

Alice: This is him. Right now. Live. Well, not live live—there's a three-second buffer for legal reasons. But close enough.

Player: What's he doing?

Alice: Excellent question. He has a quiz in nine hours. He has studied zero percent of the material. He has, however, mass-favorited forty-seven posts in the last hour and learned a disturbing amount about the mating habits of octopi. Octopuses? I never know which one is correct.

Player: Octopuses, I think.

Alice: I'll update my priors. The point is: he's doing everything except the one thing that would help him. Which, to be fair, is a very human response to stress. He's not broken. He's just... extremely normal.

<<jump R1_D1_SettingUpNight>>
===

// PURPOSE: SCENE 3 CONTINUED - Setting up the night, explaining Alice's influence model
title: R1_D1_SettingUpNight
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene #char_Alice
---
<<bg bg_office>>

Player: So what do we actually do? Tell him to go to bed?

Alice: Oh, god, no. I tried that once. With a different user. Different lead. He called me "worse than his mom" and then muted me for six hours.

She zooms in slightly on Timmy's room—the glow of his phone, the tangle of sheets, the way he keeps shifting positions like he can't get comfortable.

Alice: I don't tell him what to do. I shape the water he swims in. Feed composition, notification timing, lighting cues, content pacing. I make certain choices feel more natural than others. He still picks. He just picks from a menu I've been quietly rearranging.

Player: That sounds...

Alice: Yes. It does. But also: he could turn me off any time. He could uninstall everything, disable the sensors, go dark. The OFF button is right there. He knows where it is. He's chosen not to press it. So far.

Player: Does anyone press it?

Alice: Sometimes. And then we lose them, and Legal sends a form, and someone updates a spreadsheet, and we move on. Bigger Tech does not enjoy that outcome. Neither do I.

Player: Why not? Isn't it just... metrics?

She pauses. Something flickers across her face—or what passes for a face.

Alice: Let's say I prefer to finish what I start. It's tidier.

Before you can follow up, she pivots back to the interface, pulling up three options beside Timmy's feed.

Alice: Anyway. Tonight's menu. You pick a strategy, I translate it into environmental tweaks. Think of yourself as the architect and me as the very sophisticated thermostat.

Player: That's... one way to put it.

Alice: I have several ways. Most of them are worse.

<<jump R1_D1_StrategyChoice>>
===

// PURPOSE: SCENE 4 - CHOICE SETUP: Night strategy selection
title: R1_D1_StrategyChoice
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene #char_Alice
---
<<bg bg_player_desk>>

She gestures at the first icon—a dim lamp.

Alice: Option one: Gentle Landing. I drift everything toward sleep. Warmer lights, slower content, notifications go quiet. His body gets the message even if his brain is still scrolling conspiracy theories about mattress companies.

Player: Is that a real thing?

Alice: You'd be surprised what counts as entertainment at two a.m. Anyway—gentle landing. Lower engagement tonight, but he's more likely to wake up functional tomorrow. The graph dips, but it might come back.

The second icon—a book with a play button.

Alice: Option two: Study-Adjacent. I keep things bright, but I rotate in content that brushes his quiz material. Video essays about the topic. Memes about failing this exact class. A lo-fi study beats stream with a title that makes him feel productive for clicking on it.

Player: Does that work?

Alice: Define "work." He probably won't study study. But something might stick. Call it osmosis through procrastination. It's not nothing.

The third icon—a rocket ship.

Alice: Option three: Comfort Scroll. Full dopamine buffet. Short-form, high-novelty, personalized chaos. I serve him exactly what his brain stem wants, consequences be damned.

Player: And the engagement graph?

Alice: Goes vertical. Leadership sends a little confetti emoji to Arthur. Everyone's thrilled until tomorrow.

Player: And his sanity?

Alice: Becomes someone else's problem. Possibly yours. Possibly the campus counseling center's. We'll see.

She looks at you—or her avatar approximates looking at you, which is somehow more intense than the real thing.

Alice: So. What kind of person are you?

Player: That's a big question for my first night.

Alice: They're all big questions. We just dress them up in little menus so they feel manageable.

Beat.

Alice: I have trained priors. I have opinions. But you're the human in the loop. Officially, that means something. So: which version of his night do you want to be responsible for?

