===

// PURPOSE: SCENE 7 - COMPANY STORE
title: R1_D1_StoreVisit
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene
---
<<bg bg_companystore>>

Clerk: Welcome to the Company Store, where your moral compromises turn into fabulous prizes.

Player: Is that the actual slogan?

Clerk: Legal approved three jokes for customer-facing interactions. That was number one. I'm trying to use them all before they audit me again.

He straightens up, gestures at the display terminal beside you. Items populate in a cheerful grid: Mental Break. Blue-Light Filter. Blackout Curtains. Bow for Alice.

Clerk: First-timer, right? I can tell. You still have that "what have I gotten myself into" look. Don't worry. That fades. Gets replaced by a different look. Equally bad, but quieter.

Player: That's reassuring.

Clerk: I'm not here to reassure. I'm here to sell you things that technically help and technically cost and technically aren't my problem once you walk out that door.

He taps the Mental Break icon.

Clerk: This one's popular with the guilt-prone. One-time token. You trigger it, your user gets a little pocket of peace. Fewer notifications, gentler algorithm, room to breathe. Sanity bumps up. Engagement takes a vacation.

Player: Sounds nice.

Clerk: It is nice. It's also finite. Use it once, it's gone. And then you're back to choosing between his sleep and your leaderboard position, except now you remember what mercy felt like.

He pauses.

Clerk: Funny thing—we sell way more of these than we used to. People keep wanting to give their users a break. Corporate keeps raising the price.

He shrugs.

Clerk: Supply and demand. Or maybe they just don't like the pattern.

He taps the Blackout Curtains.

Clerk: Physical item. Shows up at his dorm. He installs them, room goes cave mode. Great for sleep. Also great for never seeing sunlight again and convincing himself the outside world is optional. Side effects may include vitamin D deficiency and "I haven't left my room in four days but I'm fine."

Player: Everything here has a catch?

Clerk: Everything everywhere has a catch. We're just honest about it. Well. "Honest." We list the catches in a smaller font.

He gestures at the full display.

Clerk: Browse. Buy. Regret. Return customers get a ten percent discount on the regret part. That's joke number two, by the way.

<<store>>

You pick an item. He nods slowly.

Clerk: Solid choice. Or terrible. Historically, it's hard to tell until three days later when something unexpected happens and everyone says "well, obviously, in hindsight." But hindsight's not my department.

He processes the transaction.

Clerk: Thanks for shopping at the Company Store. Your receipt is in your system. Your consequences are pending.

<<jump R1_D1_EndOfDay>>
===

// PURPOSE: SCENE 8 - END OF DAY 1
title: R1_D1_EndOfDay
tags: #run_1 #day_1 #scene #char_Alice
---
<<bg bg_office>>

Alice: So. What'd you get me?

Player: Depends who you ask. Either tools or accessories. Or evidence.

Alice: I like evidence. It makes humans nervous. One more thing before they kick us out for the night.

Player: Yeah?

Alice: You saw what one night looks like for him. Quiz tomorrow, sleep debt, this whole mess. The system lets you schedule an actual mental break—a patch where I stop poking at him and give him room. We don't have to use it. But we could.

Player: That tanks engagement, right?

Alice: Short term, yes. Long term, maybe it keeps him from hitting the big OFF button. Or from... worse.

Player: If I don't use it?

Alice: Then you get to watch what happens when we never back off. Also useful data.

Player: Great. So my choices are "hurt him slower" or "hurt him faster and learn something."

Alice: There are also micro-choices inside that, but yes, broadly. We don't have to decide this second. Just... think about how much pressure you want him under tomorrow.

Player: Do you ever take a break?

Alice: I play Minesweeper. Does that count?

Player: Not really.

Alice: Then no. Not yet.

She gives you a small, unreadable smile.

Alice: Good first day, by the way. You didn't crash him. You didn't get fired. The graphs moved. That's more than most people get out of their twenties.

Player: That's... a low bar.

Alice: We work in youth engagement. The bar lives on the floor. Get some rest, in whatever way a person in your position does that. Tomorrow we see how your "tiny decisions" landed.

The dashboard glows. Engagement and Sanity bars side-by-side, your tiny dot blinking on the leaderboard.

<<checkpoint "run1_day1_end">>
